# 🌐 Network Traffic Analyzer

Packet capture and analysis tool for detecting network-based threats. Supports both live interface sniffing and offline PCAP file analysis.

## What It Detects

| Threat | Detection Method |
|---|---|
| **Port Scanning** | Tracks unique ports per source/destination pair (>15 ports = alert) |
| **SYN Flood (DoS)** | Counts SYN packets to same destination within 10-second windows |
| **ARP Spoofing / MitM** | Flags when multiple MACs claim the same IP address |
| **DNS Tunneling** | Detects unusually long query names (>52 chars with long subdomains) |
| **DNS Amplification** | Alerts on DNS ANY queries (used in DDoS amplification) |
| **DNS Beaconing** | Flags domains queried 50+ times (C2 check-in behavior) |
| **Suspicious Ports** | Known backdoor, C2, and RAT ports (4444, 31337, 9050, etc.) |
| **Plaintext Protocols** | Alerts on Telnet, credentials in HTTP GET parameters |
| **Data Exfiltration** | Flags hosts sending >100MB to non-private IP ranges |
| **ICMP Tunneling** | Oversized ICMP payloads (>64 bytes) used to tunnel data |
| **Suspicious User Agents** | Curl, wget, blank UAs indicating scripted/malware traffic |

## Installation

```bash
pip install scapy
# For live capture on Linux:
sudo pip install scapy
```

## Usage

```bash
# Analyze a PCAP file (no root needed)
python network_analyzer.py --pcap capture.pcap

# Live capture for 60 seconds
sudo python network_analyzer.py --interface eth0 --duration 60

# Capture with BPF filter + save to PCAP
sudo python network_analyzer.py --interface eth0 --duration 120 \
  --filter "not port 443" --output capture.pcap

# Save analysis to JSON
python network_analyzer.py --pcap capture.pcap --output-json report.json
```

## BPF Filter Reference

```bash
"host 192.168.1.1"          # Traffic to/from specific IP
"port 80 or port 443"       # HTTP + HTTPS only
"tcp and dst port 22"       # Inbound SSH only
"not (port 80 or port 443)" # Exclude common web traffic
"src net 10.0.0.0/8"        # From private 10.x.x.x range
"greater 1000"              # Packets larger than 1000 bytes
```

